1. The Core Idea: Orbital Compute Nodes

Imagine servers in orbit instead of warehouses on Earth.

Each orbital node could:
	•	Receive data directly from Earth-observation satellites
	•	Process that data in space
	•	Send only the useful results back to Earth

Instead of sending petabytes of raw imagery down to Earth and processing it later, you process it where it’s generated.

Example flow:

Satellite → Orbital Compute Node → Processed Data → Earth

That reduces bandwidth and latency.

⸻

2. Why Space Is Actually Good for Computers

❄️ Natural Cooling

Data centers on Earth spend huge energy cooling servers.

In space:
	•	Vacuum = excellent heat radiation
	•	Huge temperature gradients
	•	Radiators can dump heat directly to space

So cooling infrastructure becomes simpler.

⸻

☀️ Near-Unlimited Solar Power

Orbital platforms can run on:
	•	Large solar arrays
	•	Continuous sunlight in certain orbits

That means no grid dependency.

⸻

📡 Direct Satellite Network Access

Most satellites already communicate in orbit.

Orbital compute nodes could act as routers + processors for:
	•	Earth imaging
	•	GPS data
	•	weather satellites
	•	military sensors
	•	deep-space communications

Think of them as space internet exchange points.

